DOCUMENT();

loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "MathObjects.pl",
  "PGML.pl",
  "answerHints.pl",
  "PGcourse.pl",
);

##############################################

Context("Numeric");

do {
   $b = random(1,5,1);
   $c = random($b+1,9,1);
   $a=random(1,10,1);
} until ($a<($b-$c)**2);

$ans = Compute("-1*($a-($b-$c)**2)");

Context("LimitedNumeric");
$ans=Compute($ans);

##############################################

TEXT(beginproblem());

BEGIN_PGML

Evaluate the following.

    [`` -[[$a]-([$b]-[$c])^{2}]=  ``][________]{$ans}

END_PGML

##############################################

$brackets = "[ ]";
$s1= ($b-$c)**2;

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

The bracket [$brackets] and parentheses ( ) have the same purpose. We usually use [$brackets] when ( ) are already used in the problem, so we can tell which pair are which.

    [``
\begin{aligned}[t]
   &\phantom{={}}{-[[$a]-([$b]-[$c])^{2}]} \\
   &= -[[$a]-([$b-$c])^{2}] \\
   &= -[[$a]-[$s1]] \\
   &= -[[$a-$s1]]\\
   &= [$ans]
\end{aligned}
    ``]

END_PGML_SOLUTION

